# Dynamic Content üß†

You can embed any JavaScript expression in JSX by wrapping it in curly braces `{}`.

```jsx
const name = "Josh";
const element = <h1>Hello, {name}</h1>;

const total = <p>Total: {5 + 5}</p>;
```

# Logic in JSX üîÄ

You cannot use `if` statements inside JSX, but you can use the ternary operator.

```jsx
const element = (
  <div>
    The user is <b>{isLoggedIn ? 'currently' : 'not'}</b> logged in.
  </div>
);
```

# Rendering to DOM üñ•Ô∏è

React applications usually have a single root DOM node.

```jsx
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom/client';

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root'));
root.render(element);
```
React only updates what's necessary (Virtual DOM).

# Fragments üß©

A common pattern is for a component to return multiple elements. Fragments let you group a list of children without adding extra nodes to the DOM.

```jsx
return (
  <>
    <td>Hello</td>
    <td>World</td>
  </>
);
```

# Listing Items üìã

Use `.map()` to convert an array of data into an array of elements.

```jsx
const numbers = [1, 2, 3];
const listItems = numbers.map((number) =>
  <li key={number.toString()}>
    {number}
  </li>
);
```
Note: Always provide a unique `key` prop.

# Hello React üíª

